}
@generic{Hintz2020,
   abstract = {The age of the digital world is changing how we respond to emergencies. It is making it possible to deliver near realtime spatially-aware information to decision makers. It is raising the public’s expectations of what information is delivered to them, and how quickly. It is demanding more of federal, regional, and local agencies, and the organizations that do business in their jurisdictions. Today’s primary challenge is finding ways to integrate data from the many applications and systems it is stored and collected in, to bring it together into a structure that can be used to support emergency response efforts and risk management. This lightning talk presentation will provide an inspirational round-up of the most innovative ways agencies and organizations are using data integration technology to make better decisions and inform the public by integrating data to provide situational awareness. It will then deliver key trends GEOINT attendees should be aware of for their emergency response efforts, including the latest in geospatial AI enablement and application integration. Attendees will gain insights into the latest trends in data integration and sharing, and equipped with ideas of how they can improve their data delivery strategy to equip emergency responders and the public during a disaster. Goals & Competencies: 1. To provide a round-up of the most innovative ways agencies and organizations are using data integration technology to make better decisions and inform the public by integrating data to provide situational awareness 2. To provide an overview of key trends GEOINT attendees should be aware of for their emergency response efforts, including: rapid enterprise data integration best practices including the value of an application integration approach to data delivery and; geospatial AI raster object detection for quick, computer automated identification of objects from aerial photographs or satellite imagery. 3. To provide insights into the latest trends in data integration and sharing, and equipped with ideas of how they can improve their data delivery strategy to equip emergency responders and the public in an emergency event.},
